#### **The ‚ÄúWHAT‚Äú: System Design & Overview**

As with the goals, the system design also changed quite a bit and quite a few times. I'll go into detail on the rationale behind those changes in upcoming issues, but for now, the final system flow looks like this:

1. Generate the parameters (font, colours, text, aesthetics, etc.) for 3 visual systems to test that are consistent with your brand  
2. Generate 30 image prompts and pin descriptions for each visual system to test for the next 90 days  
3. Every day, pick an image prompt to generate an image using AI and post it on Pinterest with the corresponding pin details  
4. Wait (24 hours or longer) and then collect pin analytics to assess and compare the performance of individual pins as well as each visual system

#### **The ‚ÄúHOW‚Äú: Tool Selection Rationale**

Broadly speaking, the main reason for choosing these tools was cost (they're all free), but there are other, more nuanced reasons for my selections:

**n8n:** Aside from having a free community version, n8n offers a high degree of technical flexibility with looping, AI agent nodes, and code nodes. I also managed to connect my n8n workflow with Claude via MCP, which gave me much stronger troubleshooting capabilities (more on that later).

**Pinterest:** As a Gen Z, I‚Äôm probably more familiar with Instagram and TikTok. I picked Pinterest because, unlike platforms like Instagram, where engagement is short-lived and driven by initial interaction, Pinterest uses a visual search engine (think Google but for images) to provide suggestions. While engagement may be initially slower, it tends to be much longer-lived.

**Pollinations.ai:** This was a new one for me, but aside from it being free to use, it is also an open-source, community-driven platform for developers. In the world of big commercial image-generation platforms like DALL-E, Midjourney, or Nano Banana, it was nice to use and promote a community platform (so please go and support them too \#notsponsored).

**ChatGPT:** Honestly, this was more force of habit than a design choice, and I‚Äôve also tested the prompts with Claude and Gemini, which arguably worked even better (depending on your creative preferences).
